## Part 3: The Frontend Brain ([app.js](file:///Users/devanshgoyal/Downloads/meta_data_remover/static/js/app.js))

HTML and CSS build the visual buttons and colors, but **Javascript runs inside the user's web browser** and controls what those buttons actually *do*.

### Handling the "Browse Files" Input
```javascript
// 1. We grab references to elements on the HTML page
const fileInput = document.getElementById('file-input');
const browseBtn = document.getElementById('browse-btn');

// 2. When the fake "Browse" button is clicked, we force a click on 
// the hidden, ugly default browser file input.
browseBtn.addEventListener('click', () => fileInput.click());

// 3. Keep track of the file the user chose in memory
let currentFile = null;

fileInput.addEventListener('change', function() {
    // When the user picks a file, save it to our variable 
    // and switch the layout to show the image preview screen!
    currentFile = this.files[0];
    showPreviewScreen();
});
```

### Sending the Image to See Metadata
```javascript
const viewMetaBtn = document.getElementById('view-meta-btn');

viewMetaBtn.addEventListener('click', async () => {
    // 1. Package the image into a "FormData" envelope so the internet can carry it
    const formData = new FormData();
    formData.append('file', currentFile);

    // 2. We use 'fetch' to shoot the envelope to our Flask server invisibly!
    // The 'await' keyword pauses the code here until the server replies.
    const response = await fetch('/api/metadata', {
        method: 'POST',
        body: formData
    });
    
    // 3. The server replied with a JSON string representing the data. 
    // We convert it into a Javascript Object so we can read it.
    const data = await response.json();
    
    // 4. We now take that data, dynamically generate HTML table rows (<tr>), 
    // and insert them into the page to show the user their privacy leaks.
    displayMetadataTable(data);
});
```

### Removing & Forcing the Browser to Download
```javascript
const removeMetaBtn = document.getElementById('remove-meta-btn');

removeMetaBtn.addEventListener('click', async () => {
    // 1. Package the dirty image and send it to the Flask server
    const formData = new FormData();
    formData.append('file', currentFile);

    const response = await fetch('/api/remove', { method: 'POST', body: formData });
    
    if (response.ok) {
        // 2. The server responded successfully with a File!
        // In Javascript, we catch raw file data as a "Blob" (Binary Large Object)
        const blob = await response.blob();
        
        // 3. We create a temporary, invisible URL link that points to the Blob memory data
        const url = window.URL.createObjectURL(blob);
        
        // 4. We build an invisible hyperlink <a> tag...
        const a = document.createElement('a');
        a.href = url;
        a.download = `clean_${currentFile.name}`; // We set the downloaded file name
        
        // 5. ...we attach it to the page, mechanically click it to force the download,
        // and then immediately delete the invisible link to clean up!
        document.body.appendChild(a);
        a.click();
        window.URL.revokeObjectURL(url);
    }
});
```

### Conclusion
By tying together this flow, we've bypassed the need for clunky page refreshes. The entire process of extracting pixels, reading logic data, and downloading files happens smoothly and asynchronously. You now officially understand full-stack web development basics!
